    \section*{Metrics}

    In a population where the amount of cats is equal to the amount of dogs. Considering the following classification results from a classifier.

    \begin{table}[h]
        \centering
        \begin{tabular}{|c|c|c|}
            \hline
            Model A & Predicted dog & Predicted cat \\
            \hline \hline
            Actual dog & 30 & 20 \\
            \hline
            Actual cat & 10 & 40 \\
            \hline \hline
        \end{tabular}
    \end{table}

    \begin{enumerate}

        \item[\textbf{T1.}] What is the accuracy of Model A?

            \sol Accuracy of the model A is the total correct predictions divided by the total prediction. In this case, we assume that dogs as positive class.

            \begin{align*}
            \text{Accuracy} &= \frac{TP + TN}{Total} \\[1em]
            \text{Accuracy} &= \frac{30 + 40}{100} \\[1em]
            \text{Accuracy} &= 70.00\%
            \end{align*}

            \ans Model A has 70.00\% accuracy.
        \pagebreak

        \item[\textbf{T2.}] Consider cats as class 1 (positive) and dogs as class 0 (negative), calculate the precision, recall, and F1.

            \sol Consider true positive (TP), false positive (FP), true negative (TN), and false negative (FN) of the model A.

            \textbf{TP} means predicted cat, actual cat. (40 predictions)

            \textbf{FP} means predicted cat, actual dog. (20 predictions)

            \textbf{TN} means predicted dog, actual dog. (30 predictions)

            \textbf{FN} means predicted dog, actual cat. (10 predictions)

            \vspace{1em}

            \noindent
            \begin{minipage}{0.5\textwidth}
                \centering
                \textbf{Precision}
                \begin{align*}
                    \text{Precision} &= \frac{TP}{TP + FP} \\[1em]
                    \text{Precision} &= \frac{40}{40 + 20} \approx 66.67\% \\[1em]
                \end{align*}
            \end{minipage}%
            \hfill
            \begin{minipage}{0.5\textwidth}
                \centering
                \textbf{Recall}
                \begin{align*}
                    \text{Recall} &= \frac{TP}{TP + FN} \\[1em]
                    \text{Recall} &= \frac{40}{40 + 10} = 80.00\% \\[1em]
                \end{align*}
            \end{minipage}
            \begin{minipage}{0.5\textwidth}
                \centering
                \textbf{F1 Score}
                \begin{align*}
                    \text{F1} &= 2 \times \frac{\text{Precision} \times \text{Recall}}{\text{Precision} + \text{Recall}} \\[1em]
                    \text{F1} &= 2 \times \frac{\cfrac{2}{3} \times 0.80}{\cfrac{2}{3} + 0.80} \approx 0.73 \\[1em]
                \end{align*}
            \end{minipage}
            \ans Model A has 66.67\% precision, 80.00\% recall, and 0.73 F1 score.
        \pagebreak

        \item[\textbf{T3.}] Consider class cat as class 0 (negative) and class dog as class 1 (positive), calculate the precision, recall, and F1.

        It is important to specify the positive class when you calculate precision, recall, and F1. If there are more than two classes, it is usually done in a one-versus-all setting where one class is considered positive and the rest of the classes are considered negative.

            \sol Consider true positive (TP), false positive (FP), true negative (TN), and false negative (FN) of the model A.

            \textbf{TP} means predicted dog, actual dog. (30 predictions)

            \textbf{FP} means predicted dog, actual cat. (10 predictions)

            \textbf{TN} means predicted cat, actual cat. (40 predictions)

            \textbf{FN} means predicted cat, actual dog. (20 predictions)

            \vspace{1em}

            \noindent
            \begin{minipage}{0.5\textwidth}
                \centering
                \textbf{Precision}
                \begin{align*}
                    \text{Precision} &= \frac{TP}{TP + FP} \\[1em]
                    \text{Precision} &= \frac{30}{30 + 10} = 75.00\% \\[1em]
                \end{align*}
            \end{minipage}%
            \hfill
            \begin{minipage}{0.5\textwidth}
                \centering
                \textbf{Recall}
                \begin{align*}
                    \text{Recall} &= \frac{TP}{TP + FN} \\[1em]
                    \text{Recall} &= \frac{30}{30 + 20} = 60.00\% \\[1em]
                \end{align*}
            \end{minipage}
            \begin{minipage}{0.5\textwidth}
                \centering
                \textbf{F1 Score}
                \begin{align*}
                    \text{F1} &= 2 \times \frac{\text{Precision} \times \text{Recall}}{\text{Precision} + \text{Recall}} \\[1em]
                    \text{F1} &= 2 \times \frac{0.75 \times 0.60}{0.75 + 0.60} \approx 0.67 \\[1em]
                \end{align*}
            \end{minipage}
            \ans Model A has 75.00\% precision, 60.00\% recall, and 0.67 F1 score.
        \pagebreak

        \item[\textbf{T4.}] Now consider a lopsided population where there are 80\% cats. What is the accuracy of Model A? Using dog as the positive class, what is the precision, recall, and F1? Explain how and why these numbers change (or does not change) from the previous questions.

            \sol First of all, we need to adjust the ratio of population from 50\% : 50\% to \\ 20\% : 80\%.

            \begin{table}[h]
                \centering
                \begin{tabular}{|c|c|c|}
                    \hline
                    Model A & Predicted dog & Predicted cat \\
                    \hline \hline
                    \rule{0pt}{4ex}
                    Actual dog & $30 \times \dfrac{20\%}{50\%} = 12$ & $20 \times \dfrac{20\%}{50\%} = 8$ \\[2ex]
                    \hline
                    \rule{0pt}{4ex}
                    Actual cat & $10 \times \dfrac{80\%}{50\%} = 16$ & $40 \times \dfrac{80\%}{50\%} = 64$ \\[2ex]
                    \hline \hline
                \end{tabular}
            \end{table}

            Therefore, true positive (TP), false positive (FP), true negative (TN), and false negative (FN) of the model A are:

            \textbf{TP} means predicted dog, actual dog. (12 predictions)

            \textbf{FP} means predicted dog, actual cat. (16 predictions)

            \textbf{TN} means predicted cat, actual cat. (64 predictions)

            \textbf{FN} means predicted cat, actual dog. (8 predictions)

            \vspace{1em}

            Next, calculate accuracy, precision, recall, and F1 score of the new population.

            \vspace{1em}

            \noindent
            \begin{minipage}{0.5\textwidth}
                \centering
                \textbf{Accuracy}
                \begin{align*}
                    \text{Accuracy} &= \frac{TP + TN}{Total} \\[1em]
                    \text{Accuracy} &= \frac{12 + 64}{100} = 76.00\% \\[1em]
                \end{align*}
            \end{minipage}%
            \hfill
            \begin{minipage}{0.5\textwidth}
                \centering
                \textbf{Precision}
                \begin{align*}
                    \text{Precision} &= \frac{TP}{TP + FP} \\[1em]
                    \text{Precision} &= \frac{12}{12 + 16} \approx 42.86\% \\[1em]
                \end{align*}
            \end{minipage}
            \begin{minipage}{0.5\textwidth}
                \centering
                \textbf{Recall}
                \begin{align*}
                    \text{Recall} &= \frac{TP}{TP + FN} \\[1em]
                    \text{Recall} &= \frac{12}{12 + 8} = 60.00\% \\[1em]
                \end{align*}
            \end{minipage}%
            \hfill
            \begin{minipage}{0.5\textwidth}
                \centering
                \textbf{F1 Score}
                \begin{align*}
                    \text{F1} &= 2 \times \frac{\text{Precision} \times \text{Recall}}{\text{Precision} + \text{Recall}} \\[1em]
                    \text{F1} &= 2 \times \frac{\cfrac{3}{7} \times 0.60}{\cfrac{3}{7} + 0.60} = 0.50 \\[1em]
                \end{align*}
            \end{minipage}
        \pagebreak

            \ans The accuracy of the model A increases from 70.00\% to 76.00\% due to increasing cat population and model's ability to predict cat prediction accurately.

            The precision of the model A decreases from 75.00\% to 42.86\% due to increasing cat population which increases false positive prediction.

            The recall of the model A remains the same (60.00\%), because the ability to predict the dog correctly remains the same.

            The F1 score of the model A decreases from 0.67 to 0.50 due to decreasing precision of the model.

        \end{enumerate}

        \pagebreak

    \section*{Hello Clustering}

	Recall from lecture that K-means has two main steps: the points assignment step, and the mean update step. After the initialization of the centroids, we assign each data point to a centroid. Then, each centroids are updated by re-estimating the means.

    Concretely, if we are given N data points, $x_{1}$, $x_{2}$, ..., $x_{N}$, and we would like to form K clusters. We do the following;

    \begin{enumerate}
        \item \textbf{Initialization:} Pick K random data points as K centroid locations $c_{1}$, $c_{2}$, ..., $c_{K}$.

        \item \textbf{Assign:} For each data point k, find the closest centroid. Assign that data point to the centroid. The distance used is typically Euclidean distance.

        \item \textbf{Update:} For each centroid, calculate the mean from the data points assigned to it.

        \item \textbf{Repeat:} repeat step 2 and 3 until the centroids stop changing (convergence).
    \end{enumerate}

    \noindent Given the following data points in x-y coordinates (2 dimensional)

    \begin{table}[h]
        \centering
        \begin{tabular}{|c|c|}
            \hline
            x & y \\
            \hline
            1 & 2 \\
            3 & 3 \\
            2 & 2 \\
            8 & 8 \\
            6 & 6 \\
            7 & 7 \\
            -3 & -3 \\
            -2 & -4 \\
            -7 & -7 \\
            \hline
        \end{tabular}
    \end{table}

    \begin{figure}[h]
        \centering
        \includegraphics[width=0.6\textwidth]{figure_01}
        \caption{Data points on $(x, y)$ coordinates}
    \end{figure}

    \pagebreak

    \begin{enumerate}
        \item[\textbf{T5.}] If the starting points are (3,3), (2,2), and (-3,-3). Describe each assign and update step. What are the points assigned? What are the updated centroids? You may do this calculation by hand or write a program to do it.

            \sol \underline{\textbf{First Iteration}}

            First, we calculate distance between each point to each selected centroids $c_{1}$, $c_{2}$, and $c_{3}$.
            \begin{table}[h]
                \centering
                \caption{The first iteration of K-means Clustering Algorithm}
                \begin{tabular}{|c|c|c|c|c|c|}
                    \hline
                    \rule{0pt}{2.5ex}
                    x & y & $c_{1} = (3, 3)$ & $c_{2} = (2, 2)$ & $c_{3} = (-3, -3)$ & Cluster \\
                    \hline
                    1 & 2 & 2.24 & 1.00 & 6.40 & Cluster 2 \\
                    3 & 3 & 0.00 & 1.41 & 8.49 & Cluster 1 \\
                    2 & 2 & 1.41 & 0.00 & 7.07 & Cluster 2 \\
                    8 & 8 & 7.07 & 8.49 & 15.56 & Cluster 1 \\
                    6 & 6 & 4.24 & 5.66 & 12.73 & Cluster 1 \\
                    7 & 7 & 5.66 & 7.07 & 14.14 & Cluster 1 \\
                    -3 & -3 & 8.49 & 7.07 & 0.00 & Cluster 3 \\
                    -2 & -4 & 8.60 & 7.21 & 1.41 & Cluster 3 \\
                    -7 & -7 & 14.14 & 12.73 & 5.66 & Cluster 3 \\
                    \hline
                \end{tabular}
            \end{table}

            Then assign each point to the closest centroid.

            \begin{itemize}
                \item \textbf{Cluster 1} contains $\lbrace(3, 3), (8, 8), (6, 6), (7, 7)\rbrace$
                \item \textbf{Cluster 2} contains $\lbrace(1, 2), (2, 2)\rbrace$
                \item \textbf{Cluster 3} contains $\lbrace(-3, -3), (-2, -4), (-7, -7)\rbrace$
            \end{itemize}

            Then re-calculate the centroid of each clusters by using the formula.
            \begin{align*}
                \text{Centroid} & = \left( \dfrac{x_{1} + x_{2} + ... + x_{N}}{N}, \ \dfrac{y_{1} + y_{2} + ... + y_{N}}{N} \right)
            \end{align*}
            These are re-calculated centroids of each cluster.
            \begin{align*}
                \text{Centroid 1}\ (c_{1}) & = \left( \dfrac{3 + 8 + 6 + 7}{4},\ \dfrac{3 + 8 + 6 + 7}{4} \right) \\
                \text{Centroid 1}\ (c_{1}) & = (6.00, 6.00) \\[0.75em]
                \text{Centroid 2}\ (c_{2}) & = \left( \dfrac{1 + 2}{2},\ \dfrac{2 + 2}{2} \right) \\
                \text{Centroid 2}\ (c_{2}) & = (1.50, 2.00) \\[0.75em]
                \text{Centroid 3}\ (c_{3}) & = \left( \dfrac{(-3) + (-2) + (-7)}{3},\ \dfrac{(-3) + (-4) + (-7)}{3} \right) \\
                \text{Centroid 3}\ (c_{3}) & = (-4.00, -4.67)
            \end{align*}
        \pagebreak

            \underline{\textbf{Second Iteration}}

            First, we calculate distance between each point to each new centroids $c_{1}$, $c_{2}$, and $c_{3}$.
            \begin{table}[h]
                \centering
                \caption{The second iteration of K-means Clustering Algorithm}
                \begin{tabular}{|c|c|c|c|c|c|}
                    \hline
                    \rule{0pt}{2.5ex}
                    x & y & $c_{1} = (6.00, 6.00)$ & $c_{2} = (1.50, 2.00)$ & $c_{3} = (-4.00, -4.67)$ & Cluster \\
                    \hline
                    1 & 2 & 6.40 & 0.50 & 8.33 & Cluster 2 \\
                    3 & 3 & 4.24 & 1.80 & 10.38 & Cluster 2 \\
                    2 & 2 & 5.66 & 0.50 & 8.97  & Cluster 2 \\
                    8 & 8 & 2.83 & 8.85 & 17.45 & Cluster 1 \\
                    6 & 6 & 0.00 & 6.02 & 14.62 & Cluster 1 \\
                    7 & 7 & 1.41 & 7.43 & 16.03 & Cluster 1 \\
                    -3 & -3 & 12.73 & 6.73 & 1.94 & Cluster 3 \\
                    -2 & -4 & 12.81 & 6.95 & 2.11 & Cluster 3 \\
                    -7 & -7 & 18.38 & 12.38 & 3.80 & Cluster 3 \\
                    \hline
                \end{tabular}
            \end{table}

            Then assign each point to the closest centroid.

            \begin{itemize}
                \item \textbf{Cluster 1} contains $\lbrace(8, 8), (6, 6), (7, 7)\rbrace$
                \item \textbf{Cluster 2} contains $\lbrace(1, 2), (3, 3), (2, 2)\rbrace$
                \item \textbf{Cluster 3} contains $\lbrace(-3, -3), (-2, -4), (-7, -7)\rbrace$
            \end{itemize}

            Then re-calculate the centroid of each clusters by using the formula.
            \begin{align*}
                \text{Centroid} & = \left( \dfrac{x_{1} + x_{2} + ... + x_{N}}{N}, \ \dfrac{y_{1} + y_{2} + ... + y_{N}}{N} \right)
            \end{align*}
            These are re-calculated centroids of each cluster.
            \begin{align*}
                \text{Centroid 1}\ (c_{1}) & = \left( \dfrac{8 + 6 + 7}{3},\ \dfrac{8 + 6 + 7}{3} \right) \\
                \text{Centroid 1}\ (c_{1}) & = (7.00, 7.00) \\[0.75em]
                \text{Centroid 2}\ (c_{2}) & = \left( \dfrac{1 + 3 + 2}{3},\ \dfrac{2 + 3 + 2}{3} \right) \\
                \text{Centroid 2}\ (c_{2}) & = (2.00, 2.33) \\[0.75em]
                \text{Centroid 3}\ (c_{3}) & = \left( \dfrac{(-3) + (-2) + (-7)}{3},\ \dfrac{(-3) + (-4) + (-7)}{3} \right) \\
                \text{Centroid 3}\ (c_{3}) & = (-4.00, -4.67)
            \end{align*}
        \pagebreak

            \underline{\textbf{Third Iteration}}

            First, we calculate distance between each point to each new centroids $c_{1}$, $c_{2}$, and $c_{3}$.
            \begin{table}[h]
                \centering
                \caption{The third iteration of K-means Clustering Algorithm}
                \begin{tabular}{|c|c|c|c|c|c|}
                    \hline
                    \rule{0pt}{2.5ex}
                    x & y & $c_{1} = (7.00, 7.00)$ & $c_{2} = (2.00, 2.33)$ & $c_{3} = (-4.00, -4.67)$ & Cluster \\
                    \hline
                    1 & 2 & 7.81 & 1.05 & 8.33 & Cluster 2 \\
                    3 & 3 & 5.66 & 1.20 & 10.38 & Cluster 2 \\
                    2 & 2 & 7.07 & 0.33 & 8.97 & Cluster 2 \\
                    8 & 8 & 1.41 & 8.25 & 17.45 & Cluster 1 \\
                    6 & 6 & 1.41 & 5.43 & 14.62 & Cluster 1 \\
                    7 & 7 & 0.00 & 6.84 & 16.03 & Cluster 1 \\
                    -3 & -3 & 14.14 & 7.31 & 1.94 & Cluster 3 \\
                    -2 & -4 & 14.21 & 7.49 & 2.11 & Cluster 3 \\
                    -7 & -7 & 19.80 & 12.97 & 3.80 & Cluster 3 \\
                    \hline
                \end{tabular}
            \end{table}

            Then assign each point to the closest centroid.

            \begin{itemize}
                \item \textbf{Cluster 1} contains $\lbrace(8, 8), (6, 6), (7, 7)\rbrace$
                \item \textbf{Cluster 2} contains $\lbrace(1, 2), (3, 3), (2, 2)\rbrace$
                \item \textbf{Cluster 3} contains $\lbrace(-3, -3), (-2, -4), (-7, -7)\rbrace$
            \end{itemize}

            Then re-calculate the centroid of each clusters by using the formula.
            \begin{align*}
                \text{Centroid} & = \left( \dfrac{x_{1} + x_{2} + ... + x_{N}}{N}, \ \dfrac{y_{1} + y_{2} + ... + y_{N}}{N} \right)
            \end{align*}
            These are re-calculated centroid of each cluster.
            \begin{align*}
                \text{Centroid 1}\ (c_{1}) & = \left( \dfrac{8 + 6 + 7}{3},\ \dfrac{8 + 6 + 7}{3} \right) \\
                \text{Centroid 1}\ (c_{1}) & = (7.00, 7.00) \\[0.75em]
                \text{Centroid 2}\ (c_{2}) & = \left( \dfrac{1 + 3 + 2}{3},\ \dfrac{2 + 3 + 2}{3} \right) \\
                \text{Centroid 2}\ (c_{2}) & = (2.00, 2.33) \\[0.75em]
                \text{Centroid 3}\ (c_{3}) & = \left( \dfrac{(-3) + (-2) + (-7)}{3},\ \dfrac{(-3) + (-4) + (-7)}{3} \right) \\
                \text{Centroid 3}\ (c_{3}) & = (-4.00, -4.67)
            \end{align*}
            Since centroid of each each cluster doesn't change, the algorithm is terminated.
            \pagebreak

            \ans Each cluster has centroid and members as following.
            \begin{itemize}
                \item \textbf{Cluster 1} has centroid at $(7.00, 7.00)$ and contains $\lbrace(8, 8), (6, 6), (7, 7)\rbrace$
                \item \textbf{Cluster 2} has centroid at $(2.00, 2.33)$ and contains $\lbrace(1, 2), (3, 3), (2, 2)\rbrace$
                \item \textbf{Cluster 3} has centroid at $(-4.00, -4.67)$ and contains $\lbrace(-3, -3), (-2, -4), \\ (-7, -7)\rbrace$
            \end{itemize}
        \pagebreak

        \item[\textbf{T6.}] If the starting points are (-3,-3), (2,2), and (-7,-7), what happens?

            \sol \underline{\textbf{First Iteration}}

            First, we calculate distance between each point to each selected centroids $c_{1}$, $c_{2}$, and $c_{3}$.
            \begin{table}[h]
                \centering
                \caption{The first iteration of K-means Clustering Algorithm}
                \begin{tabular}{|c|c|c|c|c|c|}
                    \hline
                    \rule{0pt}{2.5ex}
                    x & y & $c_{1} = (-3, -3)$ & $c_{2} = (2, 2)$ & $c_{3} = (-7, -7)$ & Cluster \\
                    \hline
                    1 & 2 & 6.40 & 1.00 & 12.04 & Cluster 2 \\
                    3 & 3 & 8.49 & 1.41 & 14.14 & Cluster 2 \\
                    2 & 2 & 7.07 & 0.00 & 12.73 & Cluster 2 \\
                    8 & 8 & 15.56 & 8.49 & 21.21 & Cluster 2 \\
                    6 & 6 & 12.73 & 5.66 & 18.38 & Cluster 2 \\
                    7 & 7 & 14.14 & 7.07 & 19.80 & Cluster 2 \\
                    -3 & -3 & 0.00 & 7.07 & 5.66 & Cluster 1 \\
                    -2 & -4 & 1.41 & 7.21 & 5.83 & Cluster 1 \\
                    -7 & -7 & 5.66 & 12.73 & 0.00 & Cluster 3 \\
                    \hline
                \end{tabular}
            \end{table}

            Then assign each point to the closest centroid.

            \begin{itemize}
                \item \textbf{Cluster 1} contains $\lbrace(-3, -3), (-2, -4)\rbrace$
                \item \textbf{Cluster 2} contains $\lbrace(1, 2), (3, 3), (2, 2), (8, 8), (6, 6), (7, 7)\rbrace$
                \item \textbf{Cluster 3} contains $\lbrace(-7, -7)\rbrace$
            \end{itemize}

            Then re-calculate the centroid of each clusters by using the formula.
            \begin{align*}
                \text{Centroid} & = \left( \dfrac{x_{1} + x_{2} + ... + x_{N}}{N}, \ \dfrac{y_{1} + y_{2} + ... + y_{N}}{N} \right)
            \end{align*}
            These are re-calculated centroids of each cluster.
            \begin{align*}
                \text{Centroid 1}\ (c_{1}) & = \left( \dfrac{(-3) + (-2)}{2},\ \dfrac{(-3) + (-4)}{2} \right) \\
                \text{Centroid 1}\ (c_{1}) & = (-2.50, -3.50) \\[0.75em]
                \text{Centroid 2}\ (c_{2}) & = \left( \dfrac{1 + 3 + 2 + 8 + 6 + 7}{6},\ \dfrac{2 + 3 + 2 + 8 + 6 + 7}{6} \right) \\
                \text{Centroid 2}\ (c_{2}) & = (4.50, 4.67) \\[0.75em]
                \text{Centroid 3}\ (c_{3}) & = \left( \dfrac{-7}{1},\ \dfrac{-7}{1} \right) \\
                \text{Centroid 3}\ (c_{3}) & = (-7.00, -7.00)
            \end{align*}
        \pagebreak

            \underline{\textbf{Second Iteration}}

            First, we calculate distance between each point to each new centroids $c_{1}$, $c_{2}$, and $c_{3}$.
            \begin{table}[h]
                \centering
                \caption{The second iteration of K-means Clustering Algorithm}
                \begin{tabular}{|c|c|c|c|c|c|}
                    \hline
                    \rule{0pt}{2.5ex}
                    x & y & $c_{1} = (-2.50, -3.50)$ & $c_{2} = (4.50, 4.67)$ & $c_{3} = (-7.00, -7.00)$ & Cluster \\
                    \hline
                    1 & 2 & 6.52 & 4.40 & 12.04 & Cluster 2 \\
                    3 & 3 & 8.51 & 2.24 & 14.14 & Cluster 2 \\
                    2 & 2 & 7.11 & 3.66 & 12.73 & Cluster 2 \\
                    8 & 8 & 15.57 & 4.83 & 21.21 & Cluster 2 \\
                    6 & 6 & 12.75 & 2.01 & 18.38 & Cluster 2 \\
                    7 & 7 & 14.16 & 3.42 & 19.80 & Cluster 2 \\
                    -3 & -3 & 0.71 & 10.73 & 5.66 & Cluster 1 \\
                    -2 & -4 & 0.71 & 10.83 & 5.83 & Cluster 1 \\
                    -7 & -7 & 5.70 & 16.38 & 0.00 & Cluster 3 \\
                    \hline
                \end{tabular}
            \end{table}

            Then assign each point to the closest centroid.

            \begin{itemize}
                \item \textbf{Cluster 1} contains $\lbrace(-3, -3), (-2, -4)\rbrace$
                \item \textbf{Cluster 2} contains $\lbrace(1, 2), (3, 3), (2, 2), (8, 8), (6, 6), (7, 7)\rbrace$
                \item \textbf{Cluster 3} contains $\lbrace(-7, -7)\rbrace$
            \end{itemize}

            Then re-calculate the centroid of each clusters by using the formula.
            \begin{align*}
                \text{Centroid} & = \left( \dfrac{x_{1} + x_{2} + ... + x_{N}}{N}, \ \dfrac{y_{1} + y_{2} + ... + y_{N}}{N} \right)
            \end{align*}
            These are re-calculated centroids of each cluster.
            \begin{align*}
                \text{Centroid 1}\ (c_{1}) & = \left( \dfrac{(-3) + (-2)}{2},\ \dfrac{(-3) + (-4)}{2} \right) \\
                \text{Centroid 1}\ (c_{1}) & = (-2.50, -3.50) \\[0.75em]
                \text{Centroid 2}\ (c_{2}) & = \left( \dfrac{1 + 3 + 2 + 8 + 6 + 7}{6},\ \dfrac{2 + 3 + 2 + 8 + 6 + 7}{6} \right) \\
                \text{Centroid 2}\ (c_{2}) & = (4.50, 4.67) \\[0.75em]
                \text{Centroid 3}\ (c_{3}) & = \left( \dfrac{-7}{1},\ \dfrac{-7}{1} \right) \\
                \text{Centroid 3}\ (c_{3}) & = (-7.00, -7.00)
            \end{align*}
        \pagebreak

            \ans Each cluster has centroid and members as following.
            \begin{itemize}
                \item \textbf{Cluster 1} has centroid at $(-2.50, -3.50)$ and contains $\lbrace(-3, -3), (-2, -4)\rbrace$
                \item \textbf{Cluster 2} has centroid at $(4.50, 4.67)$ and contains $\lbrace(1, 2), (3, 3), (2, 2), \\ (8, 8), (6, 6), (7, 7)\rbrace$
                \item \textbf{Cluster 3} has centroid at $(-7.00, -7.00)$ and contains $\lbrace(-7, -7)\rbrace$
            \end{itemize}
            As we choose different initial centroid points, sometimes it gives different clustering results.
        \pagebreak

        \item[\textbf{T7.}] Between the two starting set of points in the previous two questions, which one do you think is better? How would you measure the 'goodness' quality of a set of starting points?

        In general, it is important to try different sets of starting points when doing k-means.

            \ans This figure below shows the data points clustering on problem \textbf{T5}.
            \begin{figure}[h]
                \centering
                \includegraphics[width=0.6\textwidth]{figure_02}
                \caption{Data points clustering on problem \textbf{T5}}
            \end{figure}

            And this figure below shows the data points clustering on problem \textbf{T6}.
            \begin{figure}[h]
                \centering
                \includegraphics[width=0.6\textwidth]{figure_03}
                \caption{Data points clustering on problem \textbf{T6}}
            \end{figure}

            To determine which has better clustering, consider these 2 factors as following.
            \begin{itemize}
                \item The data point should be as near as possible to their cluster.
                \item The data point should be as far as possible to the other cluster.
            \end{itemize}

            In my opinion, data points clustering on problem \textbf{T5} is better, because the clusters on problem \textbf{T5} are not too large compared to the cluster 2 of problem \textbf{T6}.
    \end{enumerate}
    \pagebreak

    \section*{My heart will go on}

    In this part of the exercise we will work on the Titanic dataset provided by Kaggle. The Titanic dataset contains information of the passengers boarding the Titanic on its final voyage. We will work on predicting whether a given passenger will survive the trip.

    \begin{lstlisting}[language=Python, caption=Import data using Pandas, gobble=8]
        TRAIN_URL = "http://s3.amazonaws.com/assets.datacamp.com/course/Kaggle/train.csv"
        TEST_URL = "http://s3.amazonaws.com/assets.datacamp.com/course/Kaggle/test.csv"

        train = pd.read_csv(TRAIN_URL)
        test = pd.read_csv(TEST_URL)
    \end{lstlisting}

    Both train and test are dataframes. Use the function \texttt{train.head()} and \texttt{train.tail()} to explore the data. What do you see?

    \vspace{0.5em}

    Use the function \texttt{describe()} to get a better understanding of the data. You can read the meaning of the data fields at \texttt{\url{https://www.kaggle.com/c/titanic/data}}

    \vspace{0.5em}

    Looking at the data, you will notice a lot of missing values. For example, some age is NaN. This is normal for real world data to have some missing values.

    \vspace{0.5em}

    There are several ways to handle missing values. The simplest is to throw away any rows that have missing values. However, this usually reduce the amount of training data you have. Another method is to guess what the missing value should be. The simplest guess is to use the Median or Mode of the data. For this exercise we will proceed with this.

    \begin{enumerate}
        \item[\textbf{T8.}] Perform the following preprocessing steps on the dataset.

            \begin{itemize}
                \item[\textbf{T8.1.}] What is the median age of the training set?

                \sol To calculate median of age column, simply use the following command.

                \begin{lstlisting}[language=Python, caption=Calculate median value of the age column, gobble=20]
                    median_age = train["Age"].median()
                    print(f"The median age is {median_age}.")
                \end{lstlisting}

                \ans The median of the age column is 28 years.

                \item[\textbf{T8.2.}] Fill the missing values with the median.

                \sol To fill the median value of age to missing values in training dataset, simply use the following command.

                \begin{lstlisting}[language=Python, caption=Fill missing age value with median value, gobble=20]
                    train["Age"] = train["Age"].fillna(median_age)
                \end{lstlisting}

            \end{itemize}
    \pagebreak

        \item[\textbf{T9.}] Perform the following preprocessing steps on the dataset.

            \begin{itemize}
                \item[\textbf{T9.1.}] Some fields like \texttt{Embarked} are categorical. They need to be converted to numbers first. We will represent \texttt{S} with \texttt{0}, \texttt{C} with \texttt{1}, and \texttt{Q} with \texttt{2}.

                \sol Convert categorical value on Embarked column from \texttt{S}, \texttt{C}, and \texttt{Q} to \texttt{0}, \texttt{1}, and \texttt{2} respectively.

                \begin{lstlisting}[language=Python, caption=Convert categorical value on \texttt{Embarked} column, gobble=20]
                    train.loc[train["Embarked"] == "S", "Embarked"] = 0
                    train.loc[train["Embarked"] == "C", "Embarked"] = 1
                    train.loc[train["Embarked"] == "Q", "Embarked"] = 2
                \end{lstlisting}

                \item[\textbf{T9.2.}] What is the mode of \texttt{Embarked}?

                \sol Calculate mode value of the \texttt{Embarked} column. Note that \texttt{mode()} returns \texttt{Series} object, not a single value.

                \begin{lstlisting}[language=Python, caption=Calculate mode value of the \texttt{Embarked} column, gobble=20]
                    mode_embarked = train["Embarked"].mode()[0]
                    print(f"The mode of embarked is {mode_embarked}.")
                \end{lstlisting}

                \ans The mode value of the \texttt{Embarked} column is 0 (Southampton).

                \vspace{1em}

                \item[\textbf{T9.3.}] Fill the missing values with the mode.

                \sol Fill the missing value on Embarked column with the mode.

                \begin{lstlisting}[language=Python, caption=Fill the missing embarked value with mode value, gobble=20]
                    train["Embarked"] = train["Embarked"].fillna(mode_embarked)
                \end{lstlisting}

                \item[\textbf{T9.4.}] Do the same for \texttt{Sex}.

                \sol Convert categorical value on \texttt{Embarked} column from \texttt{male}, \texttt{female} to \texttt{0} and \texttt{1} respectively.

                \begin{lstlisting}[language=Python, caption=Repeat the process on the \texttt{Sex} column., gobble=20]
                    # Convert categorical value to 0 and 1
                    train.loc[train["Sex"] == "male", "Sex"] = 0
                    train.loc[train["Sex"] == "female", "Sex"] = 1

                    # Calculate mode value of the Sex column.
                    mode_sex = train["Sex"].mode()[0]
                    print(f"The mode of sex is {mode_sex}.")

                    # Fill missing value with mode value
                    train["Sex"] = train["Sex"].fillna(mode_sex)
                \end{lstlisting}

                \ans The mode value of the \texttt{Sex} column is 0 (male).

            \end{itemize}
    \pagebreak

        \item[\textbf{T10.}] Write a linear regression classifier using gradient descent as learned in class. Use \texttt{Pclass}, \texttt{Sex}, \texttt{Age}, and \texttt{Embarked} as input features with threshold value 0.5.

            \sol For this problem, set the configuration as following.

            \begin{lstlisting}[language=Python, caption=Configuration for problem \textbf{T10}, gobble=16]
                INPUT_FEATURES = ["Pclass", "Sex", "Age", "Embarked"]
                OUTPUT_FEATURE = "Survived"
                OUTPUT_FILENAME = "submission.csv"
                ID_COLUMN = "PassengerId"

                CLASSIFICATION_THRESHOLD = 0.50
            \end{lstlisting}

            Train a linear regression model from \texttt{scikit-learn} library.

            \begin{lstlisting}[language=Python, caption=Train a linear regression model, gobble=16]
                # Extract data from train dataset
                X = train[INPUT_FEATURES]
                y = train[OUTPUT_FEATURE]

                # Train the linear regression model
                model = LinearRegression()
                model.fit(X, y)
            \end{lstlisting}

            Use pre-trained model from the previous step to predict test dataset.

            \begin{lstlisting}[language=Python, caption=Prediction on test dataset using linear regression model, gobble=16]
                # Extract data from test dataset
                X_test = test[INPUT_FEATURES]

                # Input test dataset into pre-trained linear regression model.
                raw_predictions = model.predict(X_test)
            \end{lstlisting}

            Create a \texttt{Pandas DataFrame} containing \texttt{PassengerId} and \texttt{Survived} columns for submission file in Kaggle competition.

            \begin{lstlisting}[language=Python, caption=Create \texttt{Pandas DataFrame} for Kaggle competition, gobble=16]
                # Initialize empty DataFrame
                submission = pd.DataFrame()

                # Add passenger ID column to the DataFrame
                submission[ID_COLUMN] = test[ID_COLUMN]

                # Add raw prediction value to the DataFrame
                submission[OUTPUT_FEATURE] = raw_predictions
            \end{lstlisting}

        \pagebreak

            Since it is classification task, the predicted value has to be \texttt{0} or \texttt{1} only. Therefore we are applying the threshold as following:
            \begin{itemize}
                \item If the predicted value is less than \texttt{0.5}, change them to \texttt{0}.
                \item If the predicted value is more than or equal to \texttt{0.5}, change them to \texttt{1}.
            \end{itemize}

            \begin{lstlisting}[language=Python, caption=Applying threshold for classification, gobble=16]
                submission[OUTPUT_FEATURE] = (
                    submission[OUTPUT_FEATURE] >= CLASSIFICATION_THRESHOLD
                ).astype(int)
            \end{lstlisting}

            Finally, save Kaggle submission file as \texttt{csv} file.

            \begin{lstlisting}[language=Python, caption=Save submission \texttt{csv} file., gobble=16]
                submission.to_csv(OUTPUT_FILENAME, index=False)
            \end{lstlisting}

        \item[\textbf{T11.}] To submit your prediction, you must first sign-up for an account on \texttt{\url{https://www.kaggle.com}}. Click participate to the competition at \texttt{\url{https://www.kaggle.com/c/titanic/}} then submit your csv file for the score. Submit a screenshot of your submission (with the scores).

            \ans The submission score from problem \textbf{T10} is 0.76315.

            \begin{figure}[h]
                \raggedleft
                \includegraphics[width=0.93\textwidth]{figure_04}
                \caption{Submission score of the problem \textbf{T10}}
            \end{figure}

    \pagebreak

        \item[\textbf{T12.}] Try adding some higher order features to your training (${x_{1}}^{2}$, ${x_{1}}{x_{2}}$, ...). Does this model has better accuracy on the training set? How does it perform on the test set?

        \sol For this problem, set the configuration as following.

            \begin{lstlisting}[language=Python, caption=Configuration for problem \textbf{T12}, gobble=16]
                INPUT_FEATURES = ["Pclass", "Sex", "Age", "Embarked"]
                OUTPUT_FEATURE = "Survived"
                OUTPUT_FILENAME = "submission_high_order.csv"
                ID_COLUMN = "PassengerId"

                CLASSIFICATION_THRESHOLD = 0.50
            \end{lstlisting}

            Use \texttt{PolynomialFeatures()} function from \texttt{scikit-learn} library to automatically apply higher order features on dataset.

            \begin{lstlisting}[language=Python, caption=Applying higher order features on both datasets, gobble=16]
                # Extract data from train dataset
                X = train[INPUT_FEATURES]
                y = train[OUTPUT_FEATURE]

                # Add high order features to the train dataset
                X_high_order = PolynomialFeatures(degree=2).fit_transform(X)

                # Extract data from test dataset
                X_test = test[INPUT_FEATURES]

                # Add high order features to the test dataset.
                X_test_high_order = PolynomialFeatures(degree=2).fit_transform(X_test)
            \end{lstlisting}

            Train a linear regression model from \texttt{scikit-learn} library with higher order features.

            \begin{lstlisting}[language=Python, caption=Train a linear regression model with higher order features, gobble=16]
                # Train the linear regression model with high order features.
                model = LinearRegression()
                model.fit(X_high_order, y)
            \end{lstlisting}

            Use pre-trained model from the previous step to predict test dataset. Make sure to apply higher order features on test dataset too.

            \begin{lstlisting}[language=Python, caption=Prediction on test dataset using linear regression model, gobble=16]
                # Input test dataset with high order features into pre-trained linear regression model.
                raw_predictions = model.predict(X_test_high_order)
            \end{lstlisting}

        \pagebreak

            Create a \texttt{Pandas DataFrame} containing \texttt{PassengerId} and \texttt{Survived} columns for submission file in Kaggle competition.

            \begin{lstlisting}[language=Python, caption=Create \texttt{Pandas DataFrame} for Kaggle competition, gobble=16]
                # Initialize empty DataFrame
                submission_high_order = pd.DataFrame()

                # Add passenger ID column to the DataFrame
                submission_high_order[ID_COLUMN] = test[ID_COLUMN]

                # Add raw prediction value to the DataFrame
                submission_high_order[OUTPUT_FEATURE] = raw_predictions
            \end{lstlisting}

            Since it is classification task, the predicted value has to be \texttt{0} or \texttt{1} only. Therefore we are applying the threshold as following:
            \begin{itemize}
                \item If the predicted value is less than \texttt{0.5}, change them to \texttt{0}.
                \item If the predicted value is more than or equal to \texttt{0.5}, change them to \texttt{1}.
            \end{itemize}

            \begin{lstlisting}[language=Python, caption=Applying threshold for classification, gobble=16]
                submission_high_order[OUTPUT_FEATURE] = (
                    submission_high_order[OUTPUT_FEATURE] >= CLASSIFICATION_THRESHOLD
                ).astype(int)
            \end{lstlisting}

            Finally, save Kaggle submission file as \texttt{csv} file.

            \begin{lstlisting}[language=Python, caption=Save submission \texttt{csv} file., gobble=16]
                submission_high_order.to_csv(OUTPUT_FILENAME, index=False)
            \end{lstlisting}

            \ans The submission score from problem \textbf{T12} is 0.77980, which is higher than score from problem \textbf{T10} (0.76315).
            \begin{figure}[h]
                \raggedleft
                \includegraphics[width=0.9\textwidth]{figure_05}
                \caption{Submission score of the problem \textbf{T12}}
            \end{figure}

    \pagebreak

        \item[\textbf{T13.}] What happens if you reduce the amount of features to just \texttt{Sex} and \texttt{Age}?

        \sol For this problem, set the configuration as following.

            \begin{lstlisting}[language=Python, caption=Configuration for problem \textbf{T13}, gobble=16]
                INPUT_FEATURES = ["Sex", "Age"]
                OUTPUT_FEATURE = "Survived"
                OUTPUT_FILENAME = "submission_reduced.csv"
                ID_COLUMN = "PassengerId"

                CLASSIFICATION_THRESHOLD = 0.50
            \end{lstlisting}

            Train a linear regression model from \texttt{scikit-learn} library.

            \begin{lstlisting}[language=Python, caption=Train a linear regression model, gobble=16]
                # Extract data from train dataset
                X = train[INPUT_FEATURES]
                y = train[OUTPUT_FEATURE]

                # Train the linear regression model
                model = LinearRegression()
                model.fit(X, y)
            \end{lstlisting}

            Use pre-trained model from the previous step to predict test dataset.

            \begin{lstlisting}[language=Python, caption=Prediction on test dataset using linear regression model, gobble=16]
                # Extract data from test dataset
                X_test = test[INPUT_FEATURES]

                # Input test dataset into pre-trained linear regression model.
                raw_predictions = model.predict(X_test)
            \end{lstlisting}

            Create a \texttt{Pandas DataFrame} containing \texttt{PassengerId} and \texttt{Survived} columns for submission file in Kaggle competition.

            \begin{lstlisting}[language=Python, caption=Create \texttt{Pandas DataFrame} for Kaggle competition, gobble=16]
                # Initialize empty DataFrame
                submission_reduced = pd.DataFrame()

                # Add passenger ID column to the DataFrame
                submission_reduced[ID_COLUMN] = test[ID_COLUMN]

                # Add raw prediction value to the DataFrame
                submission_reduced[OUTPUT_FEATURE] = raw_predictions
            \end{lstlisting}

        \pagebreak

            Since it is classification task, the predicted value has to be \texttt{0} or \texttt{1} only. Therefore we are applying the threshold as following:
            \begin{itemize}
                \item If the predicted value is less than \texttt{0.5}, change them to \texttt{0}.
                \item If the predicted value is more than or equal to \texttt{0.5}, change them to \texttt{1}.
            \end{itemize}

            \begin{lstlisting}[language=Python, caption=Applying threshold for classification, gobble=16]
                submission_reduced[OUTPUT_FEATURE] = (
                    submission_reduced[OUTPUT_FEATURE] >= CLASSIFICATION_THRESHOLD
                ).astype(int)
            \end{lstlisting}

            Finally, save Kaggle submission file as \texttt{csv} file.

            \begin{lstlisting}[language=Python, caption=Save submission \texttt{csv} file., gobble=16]
                submission_reduced.to_csv(OUTPUT_FILENAME, index=False)
            \end{lstlisting}

            \ans The submission score from problem \textbf{T13} is 0.76555, which is slightly higher than score from problem \textbf{T10} (0.76315).

            \begin{figure}[h]
                \raggedleft
                \includegraphics[width=0.93\textwidth]{figure_06}
                \caption{Submission score of the problem \textbf{T13}}
            \end{figure}

    \end{enumerate}

